Project: Twitter US Airline Sentiment - Ike Imala¶

Data Description:¶

  • A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline.
  • Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:¶

  • The project is from a dataset from Kaggle.
  • Link to the Kaggle project site:https://www.kaggle.com/crowdflower/twitter-airline-sentiment
  • The dataset has to be downloaded from the above Kagglewebsite.

Objective:¶

  • To classify the sentiment of tweets into the positive, neutral & negative.

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
In [ ]:
# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

In [ ]:
# Count the occurrences of each unique airline tweets
airline_counts = data['airline'].value_counts()

# Calculate the total number of tweets
total_tweets = len(data)

# Calculate the percentage for each airline
percentage_tweets = (airline_counts / total_tweets) * 100

# Print the percentage for each airline
print(percentage_tweets)

In [ ]:
# Check for distribution of airline_sentiment

  • Negative tweets are mostly common sentiments observed with 62%, 21.2% and 16.1% respectively for neutral and positive

What is the distribution of sentiments for each airline?¶

In [ ]:
# Plot the individual airline sentiment distribution for each airline
airline_sentiment = data.groupby(['airline', 'airline_sentiment']).airline_sentiment.count().unstack()

# Plot the barplot
airline_sentiment.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Distribution of Sentiments for Each Airline')
plt.xlabel('Airline')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='Sentiment')
plt.show()
  • Ngeative tweets are more common with most of the airlines, followed by neutral and then positive.
  • It appears customers have negative sentiment about the airlines.
  • United and US Airways are the two airlines with the most negative sentiment, which could also mean passengers fly united airline more
  • Virgin has the least negative sentiment perhaps they have less customers flying the airline.

Plot of all the negative reasons for all airline¶

In [ ]:
# Plot the distribution of negative reason for all airline
negative_reason = data.groupby(['airline_sentiment', 'negativereason']).negativereason.count().unstack()

# Plot the barplot
negative_reason.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Plot of all negative issues for all Airline')
plt.xlabel('airline')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='negative reason', fontsize='small', loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.show()
  • Customer service issue concerns was a major reason behind negative sentiment for all airlines, with late flight being the other major concern.
  • Although some reasons were due to dammaged lauguage, however it was the least reason behind negative sentiments.

Plot of all the negative reasons based on each airline¶

In [ ]:
negative_reason = data.groupby(['airline', 'negativereason']).negativereason.count().unstack()

# Plot the barplot
negative_reason.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Distribution of negative reason based on each Airline')
plt.xlabel('negative')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='Sentiment', fontsize='small', loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.show()
  • United, US Airways and American are the three airlines has the higest no of negative concerns with most customer service issues.
  • Delta Airline has the most concerns in late flight
  • American Airline seems to have more canceled flight compared to the others.
  • Virgin Atlantic has few complains, perhaps due to less customers.

words = ' '.join(data['text'])
cleaned_word = " ".join([word for word in words.split()
                            if 'http' not in word
                                and not word.startswith('@')
                                and word != 'RT'
                            ])

Data Pre-processing:¶

Perform the below steps for data preprocessing.

  • Remove html tags.
  • Replace contractions in string. (e.g. replace I'm --> I am) and so on.\
  • Remove numbers.
  • Tokenization
  • To remove Stopwords.
  • Lemmatized data
  • We have used NLTK library to tokenize words , remove stopwords and lemmatize the remaining words.

  • Acronyms, stopwords, abbrevations, uppercase letters, punctuations marks, special characters like (@, ?) add to the noise in the unsctructured text and add no value to the meaning of the text, acronyms, out-of-vocabulary words, stopwords
In [ ]:
# Removing the html tags
def strip_html(text):
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser")
    return soup.get_text()

# Apply strip html function on text column
df['text'] = data['text'].apply(strip_html)

Applying the contraction library and displaying new dataframe with text column to show contraction removed¶

In [ ]:
# Apply replace contractions function on text column
def replace_contractions(text):
    """Replace contractions in string of text"""
    return contractions.fix(text)

df['text'] = df['text'].apply(replace_contractions)

Removing text with numbers and displaying text without numbers¶

In [ ]:
def remove_numbers(text):
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)  # Remove numbers using regular expression substitution
    return text

# Apply remove_numbers to the 'text' column
df['text'] = df['text'].apply(remove_numbers)

Apply Stopwords¶

In [ ]:
# Define default set of stopwords from the NLTK library using stopwords.words('english')
stopwords = stopwords.words('english')

# Define a custom list of words (customlist) that needs to be excluded from the stopwords list
customlist = ['not', "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn',
        "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',
        "mustn't", 'needn', "needn't", 'shan', "shan't", 'shouldn', "shouldn't", 'wasn',
        "wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]

# Removing the customlist from the stopwords list
# Subtracting the words in customlist from the original stopwords, so we don't remove the words in the custom list in the Text
stopwords = list(set(stopwords) - set(customlist))
In [ ]:
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

def normalize(words):
    words = remove_non_ascii(words)
    words = to_lowercase(words)
    words = remove_punctuation(words)
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

df['text'] = df.apply(lambda row: normalize(row['text']), axis=1)

Optimize the parameter: The number of trees in the random forest model(n_estimators)¶

In [ ]:
# Finding optimal number of base learners using k-fold CV ->
base_ln = [x for x in range(1, 25)]
In [ ]:
# Initializing an empty list to store the scores
cv_scores = []

for b in base_ln:
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=b) # Apply Random Forest Classifier
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')  # Perform cross-validation score on the classifier (clf) for accuracy
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())  # Append the mean score to cv_scores list

print(cv_scores)

[0.621819089915726, 0.6585857254740121, 0.6620099609347522, 0.6753616466494399, 0.6917273358251302, 0.6952191733924862, 0.7076143232989265, 0.6931649416366136, 0.7061056684471916, 0.7002872913667209, 0.693849568312597, 0.7067901544320063, 0.7042590030623778, 0.7069280552259736, 0.7052150699000623, 0.6960412318918741, 0.7031608615927178, 0.6983688734858112, 0.7026823474790487, 0.7017915847922226, 0.6998056351502816, 0.6987110578568985, 0.7013137975829257, 0.7015872074209902]
  • Above, a loop is done to perform cross-validation with different values of n_estimators for a Random Forest Classifier and stores the mean accuracy scores in the cv_scores list.

  • The cv_scores shows the mean accuracy scores for each value of n_estimators.

  • We can conclude that the performance of the Random Forest Classifier changes with different numbers of trees (n_estimators), with an maximum percentage score of 71%. Hence, even with cross-validation optimal parameter search we are not able to obtain a higher CV metric score.

In [ ]:
# plot the error as k increases
error = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]                                 # Error corresponds to each number of estimator
optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]                # Choosing the optimal number of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
plt.plot(base_ln, error)                                           # Plot between each number of estimator and misclassification error
xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()
  • As obsevered the higher the n_estimator the lesser the mis-classification error.

    plt.show()

Sequential model - LSTM¶

Using Neural Network for Sentiment Analysis¶

In [ ]:
# Used to create the Sequential model
from keras.models import Sequential
import tensorflow
# Used to create the tokens from the text data
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer

# Helps to pad the sequences into the same length
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences

# Layers that are used to implement the LSTM model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Embedding, LSTM, SpatialDropout1D

Components of the LSTM

The LSTM cell contains the following components:

  • Forget Gate f ( a neural network with sigmoid)
  • Candidate layer C"(a NN with Tanh)
  • Input Gate I ( a NN with sigmoid )
  • Output Gate O( a NN with sigmoid)
  • Hidden state H ( a vector )
  • Memory state C ( a vector)

Inputs to the LSTM cell at any step are Xt (current input) , Ht-1 (previous hidden state ) and Ct-1 (previous memory state).

Outputs from the LSTM cell are Ht (current hidden state ) and Ct (current memory state)

Working of gates in LSTM

First, LSTM cell takes the previous memory state Ct-1 and does element wise multiplication with forget gate (f) to decide if present memory state Ct. If forget gate value is 0 then previous memory state is completely forgotten else f forget gate value is 1 then previous memory state is completely passed to the cell ( Remember f gate gives values between 0 and 1 ).

Ct = Ct-1 * ft

Calculating the new memory state:

Ct = Ct + (It * C`t)

Now, we calculate the output:

Ht = tanh(Ct)

Tokenizing and converting the text into numerical vectors¶

In [ ]:
# Creating the tokenizer with 700 vocab size
tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words = 1000, split = ' ')

tokenizer.fit_on_texts(df['text'].values)

# converting text to sequences
X = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(df['text'].values)

# Padding the sequences
X = pad_sequences(X)
In [ ]:
model = Sequential()

# Model will take as input an integer matrix of size (batch, input_length), and the largest integer (i.e. word index) in the input
# input_length is X_data[1] = 1000 here.
model.add(Embedding(1000, 120, input_length = X.shape[1]))

model.add(SpatialDropout1D(0.2))

 # return_sequences = True means each LSTM cell in it is outputting its value.The output of the layer is a sequence of outputs.
model.add(LSTM(150, dropout = 0.2, recurrent_dropout = 0.2))

model.add(Dense(3, activation = 'softmax'))

# compile the model
model.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', optimizer = 'adam', metrics = ['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
print(model.summary())

Model: "sequential"
_________________________________________________________________
 Layer (type)                Output Shape              Param #   
=================================================================
 embedding (Embedding)       (None, 21, 120)           120000    
                                                                 
 spatial_dropout1d (SpatialD  (None, 21, 120)          0         
 ropout1D)

 dense (Dense)               (None, 3)                 453

Total params: 283,053
Trainable params: 283,053
Non-trainable params: 0
_________________________________________________________________
None

A sequential model is constructed by adding various layers to it.

  • The first layer is the Embedding layer which transforms one-hot encoded sparse vectors into Word Embedding vectors. As the model continues to train, the weights of the Embedding layer are adjusted so that words with similar meanings are located closer together in the vector space, or have similar Word Embedding Vectors. For example, "orange" would be located near "tangerine" and "queen" would be near "empress." The vocabulary size is specified.

  • The subsequent layer is an LSTM layer with 150 neurons. The input for this layer is a list of sentences, where each word has been converted to its corresponding Embedding vector and padded to have the same length. To prevent bias, a dropout layer is employed to regulate the network.

  • The final layer is a Dense layer which serves as the output layer and has 3 cells to perform classification, representing the 3 different categories in this dataset.

  • The model is then compiled using the Adam optimizer and categorical cross-entropy. The Adam optimizer is currently the best choice for handling sparse gradients and noisy problems, and categorical cross-entropy is typically used when the classes are mutually exclusive, meaning each sample belongs to exactly one class.

LSTM - Model 2 - The subsequent layer is an LSTM layer with 100 neurons¶

In [ ]:
model2 = Sequential()

# Model will take as input an integer matrix of size (batch, input_length), and the largest integer (i.e. word index) in the input
# input_length is X_data[1] = 1000 here.
model2.add(Embedding(1000, 120, input_length = X.shape[1]))

model2.add(SpatialDropout1D(0.2))

 # return_sequences = True means each LSTM cell in it is outputting its value.The output of the layer is a sequence of outputs.
model2.add(LSTM(100, dropout = 0.2, recurrent_dropout = 0.2))


model2.add(Dense(3, activation = 'softmax'))

# compile the model
model2.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', optimizer = 'adam', metrics = ['accuracy'])

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • For sentiment analysis, we used two supervised learning approaches, TF-IDF and Bag-of-Words. Both approach gave very similar results. They both performed well on classifying negative sentiments accurately but failed for positive and neutral.

  • We observed from the analysis that negative sentiment were the most common emotions, which shows customers were not satisfied with the quality of most of the airlines, especially United, US airways and American airline.

  • LSTM was used to determine if neural network algorithm would provide a better model accuracy, it showed that traditional approach gave similar model accuracy to LSTM. Offcourse we could implement further parameterization to improve overfitting of the LSTM model.

  • Although the loss function increased on the LSTM model, indicating the traditional approach might be better off.

  • Majority of the negative sentiments were related to customer service, late flight and canceled flight.
